    pearls: ["The single most important stewardship action is obtaining cultures BEFORE starting antibiotics -- pre-treatment cultures enable targeted de-escalation at 48-72 hours; post-antibiotic cultures have significantly reduced yield and may miss the causative organism entirely","Know the 'bugs and drugs' for each infection site: CAP = S. pneumoniae + atypicals → ceftriaxone + azithromycin; UTI = E. coli → nitrofurantoin; SSTI = Strep/Staph → cephalexin (add MRSA coverage for purulent); meningitis = S. pneumoniae + N. meningitidis → ceftriaxone + vancomycin","Procalcitonin (PCT) is the NP's best tool for antibiotic stewardship: PCT <0.25 strongly suggests viral etiology and supports withholding antibiotics; serial PCT measurements guide safe early discontinuation; PCT decreases by 50% daily with effective antibiotic therapy -- failure to decline suggests treatment failure","True penicillin allergy (IgE-mediated) occurs in only 1-2% of patients who report it; 80-90% of patients labeled 'penicillin allergic' can safely receive penicillins or cephalosporins; detailed allergy history (what exactly happened, how long after the dose, how was it treated) is the most valuable stewardship intervention the NP can perform","The fluoroquinolone 'black box' warnings include tendon rupture (especially Achilles), QTc prolongation, peripheral neuropathy, aortic dissection, and CNS effects; reserve fluoroquinolones for infections where no safer alternative exists; never use for uncomplicated UTI in young healthy patients when nitrofurantoin or TMP-SMX are appropriate","De-escalation and IV-to-PO conversion are the hallmarks of good stewardship: most hospitalized patients can convert to oral antibiotics when afebrile ≥24 hours, clinically improving, tolerating oral intake, and no reason to maintain IV access; oral bioavailability of fluoroquinolones and linezolid is near 100%","For C. difficile infection, STOP the causative antibiotic if possible; treat with oral vancomycin 125 mg QID × 10 days (first-line) or fidaxomicin 200 mg BID × 10 days (lower recurrence rate); metronidazole is no longer first-line; DO NOT use anti-motility agents (loperamide) as they worsen toxin exposure"],
